Histopathologic Cancer Detection¶

Peer-graded Assignment 3 for DTSA 5511 (Introduction to Deep Learning)

1. Introduction¶

1.1 Background¶

Statement from the website: In this competition, you must create an algorithm to identify metastatic cancer in small image patches taken from larger digital pathology scans. The data for this competition is a slightly modified version of the PatchCamelyon (PCam) benchmark dataset (the original PCam dataset contains duplicate images due to its probabilistic sampling, however, the version presented on Kaggle does not contain duplicates). PCam is highly interesting for both its size, simplicity to get started on, and approachability. In the authors' words: [PCam] packs the clinically-relevant task of metastasis detection into a straight-forward binary image classification task, akin to CIFAR-10 and MNIST. Models can easily be trained on a single GPU in a couple hours, and achieve competitive scores in the Camelyon16 tasks of tumor detection and whole-slide image diagnosis. Furthermore, the balance between task-difficulty and tractability makes it a prime suspect for fundamental machine learning research on topics as active learning, model uncertainty, and explainability.

1.2 Objectives¶

This project is about building machine learning models on histopathologic cancer detection. The data is originated from Kaggle and the problem belongs to *binary classification problem*. Multiple CNN architectures will be tested and compared in this project. Comparison will be based on classification evaluation metrics (accuracy and area under ROC curve). Hyperparamter tuning and training results comparison are the main part of this study. In addition, data handling and analysis techniques required for model training will be demostrated.

1.3 Data Source¶

  • Will Cukierski. (2018). Histopathologic Cancer Detection. Kaggle. https://kaggle.com/competitions/histopathologic-cancer-detection

2. Data Preparation and Exploratory Data Analysis¶

2.1 Training vs Testing Data¶

In this dataset, we are provided with a large number of small pathology images to classify. Files are named with an image id. The train_labels.csv file provides the ground truth for the images in the train folder. We are going to predict the labels for the images in the test folder. A positive label indicates that the center 32x32px region of a patch contains at least one pixel of tumor tissue. Tumor tissue in the outer region of the patch does not influence the label. This outer region is provided to enable fully-convolutional models that do not use zero-padding, to ensure consistent behavior when applied to a whole-slide image.

3. Model Architecture¶

3.1 First Model¶

  • Since CNN has already become the de facto method for solving computer vision problems, we only test CNN architectures in this study.
  • Considering image resolution, data size, and image category, we don't apply transfer learning from some popular state-of-the-art models.
  • We begin with a relatively simple model: CONV(32) + MaxPool(2) + CONV(64) + MaxPool(2) + Linear(1)
In [13]:
class Model1(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, img_size):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 32, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.relu1 = nn.ReLU()
        self.maxpool1 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size = 2)
        img_size = img_size // 2
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(32, 64, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.relu2 = nn.ReLU()
        self.maxpool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size = 2)
        img_size = img_size // 2
        self.flatten = nn.Flatten()
        self.linear1 = nn.Linear(64*img_size*img_size, 1)
        self.sigmoid1 = nn.Sigmoid()
    
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.maxpool1(self.relu1(self.conv1(x)))
        x = self.maxpool2(self.relu2(self.conv2(x)))
        x = self.flatten(x)
        x = self.sigmoid1(self.linear1(x))
        return x

Utility function for training logic.

In [14]:
def train_model(model, dl_train, dl_val, optimizer, criterion = nn.BCELoss(), n_epochs = 10, verbose = True):
    start_time = datetime.datetime.now()
    training_loss, val_loss, training_acc, val_acc = [], [], [], []
    for epoch in range(1, n_epochs+1):
        tl, vl, t_acc, v_acc = 0.0, 0.0, Accuracy(task = "binary"), Accuracy(task = "binary")
        t_acc.to(device), v_acc.to(device)

        for images, labels in dl_train:
            images, labels = images.to(device), labels.float().to(device)
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            outputs = model(images).squeeze()
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()
            tl += loss.item()
            t_acc(outputs, labels)
        
        model.eval()
        with torch.no_grad():
            for images, labels in dl_val:
                images, labels = images.to(device), labels.float().to(device)
                outputs = model(images).squeeze()
                loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
                vl += loss.item()
                v_acc(outputs, labels)
        model.train()
        
        time, tl, vl, ta, va = datetime.datetime.now(), tl / len(dl_train), vl / len(dl_val), t_acc.compute(), v_acc.compute()
        training_loss.append(tl), val_loss.append(vl), training_acc.append(ta.item()), val_acc.append(va.item())
        training_time = datetime.datetime.now() - start_time
        
        if verbose:
            fmt_str = '{} Epoch {}, Training loss {:.4f}, Validation loss {:.4f}, Training Acc {:.4f}, Validation Acc {:.4f}'
            print(fmt_str.format(time, epoch, tl, vl, ta, va))

    return training_loss, val_loss, training_acc, val_acc, training_time

Utility function for plotting training results.

In [15]:
def plot_loss_and_acc(training_loss, val_loss, training_acc, val_acc):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (12, 5))
    ax[0].plot(range(1, len(training_loss)+1), training_loss, '.-', linewidth=1, label="training")
    ax[0].plot(range(1, len(val_loss)+1), val_loss, '.-', linewidth=1, label="validation")
    ax[0].legend()
    ax[0].set_xlabel("epoch")
    ax[0].set_ylabel("loss")
    ax[1].plot(range(1, len(training_acc)+1), training_acc, '.-', linewidth=1, label="training")
    ax[1].plot(range(1, len(val_acc)+1), val_acc, '.-', linewidth=1, label="validation")
    ax[1].legend()
    ax[1].set_xlabel("epoch")
    ax[1].set_ylabel("accuracy")

3.3 Model Candidates¶

In addtition to Model1, we design 3 other architectures for further training and parameter tuning:

  • Model2: CONV(64)*2+MaxPool(2)+CONV(128)*2+MaxPool(2)+CONV(256)*2+MaxPool(2)+Linear(512)+Linear(64)+Linear(1)
  • Model3: Same as Model2 except with BatchNorm2D after every CONV
  • Model4: Same as Model3 except with one Dropout in the middle

The above models all have similar complexity, but Model3 and Model4 have regularization mechanisms added.

In [18]:
class Model2(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, img_size):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 64, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.relu1 = nn.ReLU()
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(64, 64, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.relu2 = nn.ReLU()
        self.maxpool1 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size = 2)
        img_size = img_size // 2
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(64, 128, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.relu3 = nn.ReLU()
        self.conv4 = nn.Conv2d(128, 128, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.relu4 = nn.ReLU()
        self.maxpool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size = 2)
        img_size = img_size // 2
        self.conv5 = nn.Conv2d(128, 256, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.relu5 = nn.ReLU()
        self.conv6 = nn.Conv2d(256, 256, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.relu6 = nn.ReLU()
        self.maxpool3 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size = 2)
        img_size = img_size // 2
        self.flatten = nn.Flatten()
        self.linear1 = nn.Linear(256*img_size*img_size, 512)
        self.relu7 = nn.ReLU()
        self.linear2 = nn.Linear(512, 64)
        self.relu8 = nn.ReLU()
        self.linear3 = nn.Linear(64, 1)
        self.sigmoid1 = nn.Sigmoid()
    
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.maxpool1(self.relu2(self.conv2(self.relu1(self.conv1(x)))))
        x = self.maxpool2(self.relu4(self.conv4(self.relu3(self.conv3(x)))))
        x = self.maxpool3(self.relu6(self.conv6(self.relu5(self.conv5(x)))))
        x = self.flatten(x)
        x = self.relu7(self.linear1(x))
        x = self.relu8(self.linear2(x))
        x = self.sigmoid1(self.linear3(x))
        return x

class Model4(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, img_size):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 64, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.bnorm1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(64)
        self.relu1 = nn.ReLU()
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(64, 64, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.bnorm2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(64)
        self.relu2 = nn.ReLU()
        self.maxpool1 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size = 2)
        img_size = img_size // 2
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(64, 128, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.bnorm3 = nn.BatchNorm2d(128)
        self.relu3 = nn.ReLU()
        self.conv4 = nn.Conv2d(128, 128, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.bnorm4 = nn.BatchNorm2d(128)
        self.relu4 = nn.ReLU()
        self.maxpool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size = 2)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(p=0.5)
        img_size = img_size // 2
        self.conv5 = nn.Conv2d(128, 256, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.bnorm5 = nn.BatchNorm2d(256)
        self.relu5 = nn.ReLU()
        self.conv6 = nn.Conv2d(256, 256, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        self.bnorm6 = nn.BatchNorm2d(256)
        self.relu6 = nn.ReLU()
        self.maxpool3 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size = 2)
        img_size = img_size // 2
        self.flatten = nn.Flatten()
        self.linear1 = nn.Linear(256*img_size*img_size, 512)
        self.relu7 = nn.ReLU()
        self.linear2 = nn.Linear(512, 64)
        self.relu8 = nn.ReLU()
        self.linear3 = nn.Linear(64, 1)
        self.sigmoid1 = nn.Sigmoid()
    
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.maxpool1(self.relu2(self.bnorm2(self.conv2(self.relu1(self.bnorm1(self.conv1(x)))))))
        x = self.dropout(self.maxpool2(self.relu4(self.bnorm4(self.conv4(self.relu3(self.bnorm3(self.conv3(x))))))))
        x = self.maxpool3(self.relu6(self.bnorm6(self.conv6(self.relu5(self.bnorm5(self.conv5(x)))))))
        x = self.flatten(x)
        x = self.relu7(self.linear1(x))
        x = self.relu8(self.linear2(x))
        x = self.sigmoid1(self.linear3(x))
        return x

result_set = []
for param in parameter_set:
    n_epochs, lr, crop_size, batch_size = param["n_epochs"], param["lr"], param["crop_size"], param["batch_size"]

    train_transforms = transforms.Compose([
        transforms.ToTensor(),
        transforms.CenterCrop(size = crop_size)
    ])
    
    if param["train_data"] == "part":
        dataset_train = ImageFolder(TRAIN_PART_LABEL0_IMAGES_PATH[:-2], transform = train_transforms)
    else:
        dataset_train = ImageFolder(TRAIN_LABEL0_IMAGES_PATH[:-2], transform = train_transforms)

    dataset_val = ImageFolder(VAL_LABEL0_IMAGES_PATH[:-2], transform = train_transforms)
    g = torch.Generator()
    g.manual_seed(0)
    dataloader_train = DataLoader(dataset_train, shuffle = True, batch_size = batch_size, num_workers = 4, generator = g)
    dataloader_val = DataLoader(dataset_val, shuffle = True, batch_size = batch_size, num_workers = 4, generator = g)

    model = param["model"]
    model.to(device)
    criterion = nn.BCELoss()
    optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr = lr)

    training_loss, val_loss, training_acc, val_acc, training_time = \
            train_model(model, dataloader_train, dataloader_val, optimizer, criterion, n_epochs, False)
    result_set.append({"training_loss": training_loss, "val_loss": val_loss, 
                        "training_acc": training_acc, "val_acc": val_acc,
                        "training_time": training_time
                      })

4. Results and Analysis¶

4.1 Results Summary¶

The following table summarizes and compares the training results of the parameter set:

  • As models getting more complex, we observe the sign of overfitting (Test case 2 and Test case 3). So, we recuit more data (the complete training data set) to train the model. However, the overfitting persists.
  • In addtion to recuiting more training data, we adjust the crop size to see how it affects the training results. From Test case 3 thru Test case 6 (crop size increases from 32x32 to full size 96x96), we can observe that training performance improves drastically (overfitting is under control and the validation accuracy improves significantly).
  • From Test case 6 to Test case 9, we tweak the learning rate and discover that it doesn't change much of the training results. It can be explained that the Adam optimizer is not sensitive to learning rate in this range (1e-3 to 3e-5). Although not shown in the table, we have tried larger learning rate (for example 0.1) and the training becomes unstable.
  • In Test case 5, 10, and 11, we test the effect of batch size. However, no obvious difference is observed in these settings.
  • We try to put more regularization in the model (Test case 12: Model4) and the result further improves. We get the best validation loss and validation accuracy. So we pick this setting as our final model.

def plot_losses(result_idx, titles):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 2, sharex = True, sharey = True, figsize = (12, 8))
    for i, idx in enumerate(result_idx):
        ax[i//2, i%2].plot(range(1, len(result_set[idx]["training_loss"])+1), result_set[idx]["training_loss"], marker = ".", linewidth = 1, label = "training")
        ax[i//2, i%2].plot(range(1, len(result_set[idx]["val_loss"])+1), result_set[idx]["val_loss"], marker = ".", linewidth = 1, label = "validation")
        ax[i//2, i%2].set_ylim([0, 1.0])
        if (i%2 == 0):
            ax[i//2, i%2].set_ylabel("Loss")
        if (i//2 == 1):
            ax[i//2, i%2].set_xlabel("# of epochs")
        ax[i//2, i%2].set_title(titles[i])
        ax[i//2, i%2].legend()
    plt.show()

final_model.eval()
with torch.no_grad():
    for images, labels in dataloader_val:
        images, labels = images.to(device), labels.float().to(device)
        outputs = final_model(images).squeeze()
        if val_outputs is None or val_labels is None:
            val_outputs = outputs
            val_labels = labels
        else:
            val_outputs = torch.concatenate((val_outputs, outputs), 0)
            val_labels = torch.concatenate((val_labels, labels), 0)

val_labels = val_labels.cpu().numpy()
final_model.train();

5. Discussion and Conclusion¶

5.1 Learning and Takeaways¶

  • GPU trains neural network much faster than CPU. In this study with my desktop environment, GPU is 8x-10x faster than CPU.
  • Although in problem description only the center 32x32px patch is used for identifying the existence of tumor tissue, using the whole image provides better results. The reason of this requires further research.
  • Comparing with other modern computer vision CNN models, the models used in this study only have moderate complexity (the final model only has 3 Conv + Pooling layers in feature selection part of the model) but still achieve decent validation accuracy.
  • Comparing with SGD, Adam is more easy to use since fewer hyperparameter tuning is required and it converges more quickly.
  • For the final model, precision = (TP)/(TP+FP) = 17,036/(17,036+746) = 95.8% and recall = (TP)/(TP+FN) = 17,036/(17,036+787) = 95.58%. Since in the case of cancer detection, misclassification cost is much high for the false negative, so it might be better to set decision threshold (currently with prediction probability > 0.5 as positive) to a lower value.
  • The difference between validation and test AUC is greater than expected (0.99 vs 0.955, the model not generalizing very well). More regularization to the model might be needed for further improvement.
  • In this study, tuning learning rate and batch size do not improve much to the model performance. Data size (quantity of images and crop size of the images), model complexity, and regularization mechanisms (especially batch normalization) help improve the model performance significantly.

5.2 Possible Future Works¶

  • Generally speaking, Adam tends to converge faster, while SGD often converges to more optimal solutions but requires more effort in parameter tuning. We may change the optimizer in this study to SGD to see if better result could be achieved.
  • Transfer learning from other state-of-the-art computer vision models.
  • It seems that more invalid images exist in the training dataset. More EDA could be done to further improve quality of training data.
